= The Relation Between Bloom's Taxonomy and PUDAL Cycle
<the-relation-between-blooms-taxonomy-and-pudal-cycle>
I often model smart systems to kavea PUDAL cycle: \[P\]erception of
Stimuli, \[U\]nderstanding, \[D\]ecision making or Deigning Plan of
Action, \[A\]cting oe Plan Executing, and \[L\]earning or Evaluationg.
what is the ost logical relation bewenn Bloom Taxonomy and PUDAL cycle?

The most logical relation between your #strong[PUDAL] cycle and
#strong[Bloom's Taxonomy] is that #strong[PUDAL represents the
#emph[Process Flow] (Time), while Bloom's represents the
#emph[Processing Depth] (Complexity).]

You can visualize this as a matrix: PUDAL is the horizontal axis (steps
you take), and Bloom's is the vertical axis (how deeply you think at
each step).

Here is the direct mapping of where each stage of your Smart System
(PUDAL) intersects with the cognitive hierarchy of Bloom's Taxonomy.

== 1. The Direct Phase Mapping
<the-direct-phase-mapping>
#strong[\[P\] Perception of Stimuli $arrow.r$ Bloom Level: Remembering]
\* #strong[The Logic:] Perception is the retrieval or recognition of
data. In a smart system, this is "sensing." In Bloom's terms, this is
the lowest level of cognition: recognizing that a specific fact or
stimulus exists. \* #emph[Bloom Action:] Recognizing, Listing,
Describing (the raw input).

#strong[\[U\] Understanding $arrow.r$ Bloom Level: Understanding] \*
#strong[The Logic:] This is a 1:1 match. The system (or person) acts on
the perceived data to determine context. It translates raw signals into
meaning. \* #emph[Bloom Action:] Interpreting, Classifying, Summarizing
(the context).

#strong[\[D\] Decision/Design $arrow.r$ Bloom Level: Analyzing &
Creating] \* #strong[The Logic:] This is the most cognitively demanding
phase. \* #strong[Decision] requires #strong[Analyzing];: Breaking down
the situation to look for patterns or causes. \* #strong[Design]
requires #strong[Creating];: Synthesizing those parts to formulate a new
plan or strategy. \* #emph[Bloom Action:] Differentiating (options),
Organizing (logic), Planning (the output).

#strong[\[A\] Acting $arrow.r$ Bloom Level: Applying] \* #strong[The
Logic:] You are executing the plan designed in the previous step. In
Bloom's, "Applying" is defined as using a procedure in a given
situation. \* #emph[Bloom Action:] Executing, Implementing, Using (the
plan).

#strong[\[L\] Learning/Evaluating $arrow.r$ Bloom Level: Evaluating] \*
#strong[The Logic:] The system looks at the result of the Action vs.~the
intent of the Design. It judges the quality of the outcome to update the
model. \* #emph[Bloom Action:] Checking, Critiquing, Judging (the delta
between expected and actual).

